    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Absolutely! Ibuprofen works by inhibiting the enzyme cyclooxygenase (COX), which is essential for the production of prostaglandins. Prostaglandins are compounds that play a key role in inflammation, pain, and fever. There are two main isoforms of COX: COX-1 and COX-2. Ibuprofen preferentially inhibits COX-2, which is more involved in inflammation and pain responses, while sparing COX-1, which helps protect the stomach lining. By blocking the COX enzymes, ibuprofen reduces the production of prostaglandins, thereby decreasing inflammation, pain, and fever.",
