      "content": "Great question! While COX-1 and COX-2 share a high degree of homology, they do have some key differences in their amino acid sequences, particularly in the active sites. One of the main differences lies in the presence of a specific amino acid, valine, at position 385 in COX-1, which is replaced by isoleucine in COX-2. This small change in the amino acid sequence alters the shape and charge of the binding pocket in COX-2, making it more hydrophobic and larger than in COX-1.\n\nThese differences in the binding pocket affect how ibuprofen interacts with each isoform. Ibuprofen can still bind to both COX-1 and COX-2, but it interacts with COX-2 in a slightly different way due to the altered pocket. The binding interactions in COX-2 are more favorable, leading to a stronger and more stable interaction with ibuprofen. This is why ibuprofen can inhibit both COX-1 and COX-2, but it has a higher affinity for COX-2, which is more involved in inflammation and pain responses.\n\nSo, while both COX-1 and COX-2 have similar active",
      "source": "target",
